    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Geotagging images</strong> is the practice of embedding <strong>GPS coordinates (latitude and longitude) into an image file's EXIF metadata</strong>. When done consistently for a business's photos — especially those uploaded to Google Business Profile — it reinforces the location entity across Google's local ecosystem and supports local pack rankings.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Metadata standard</div>
            <div class="tms-value">EXIF 2.32</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Time to impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">4-8 weeks</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Image geotagging isn't a silver bullet. But it's one of the few low-effort signals that consistently show up when local businesses out-rank competitors with weaker Google Business Profiles.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is image geotagging?</h2>
        <p>Image geotagging is the process of writing GPS coordinates into an image file's EXIF metadata block. EXIF (Exchangeable Image File Format) is the standard that stores camera settings, timestamps, and — critically — location data inside JPG, PNG, HEIC, and RAW files.</p>
        <p>The image itself looks the same. But when a crawler, a maps platform, or a photo library reads the file, the location coordinates come through as attached metadata. Google Business Profile, Google Maps, Bing Places, and photo-search tools can all read these signals.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's stance in 2024</div>
          <p>Google's John Mueller has said EXIF location data isn't a direct ranking factor for organic web search, but it's <em>useful context</em> — especially for Google Photos, Maps, and Business Profile. Local search practitioners treat it as a reinforcing signal alongside the primary ones (NAP, reviews, citations).</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why geotagging images matters</h2>
        <p>Four reasons local SEO teams still bother with it:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Local pack reinforcement.</strong> Photos with consistent EXIF coordinates align with the GBP address and support the location entity signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive differentiation.</strong> Most SMBs upload phone photos with location stripped. Geotagged, filename-optimised images stand out to Google's local systems.</li>
          <li><strong>Fewer wasted local pack impressions.</strong> Cleaner location signals mean impressions match the actual service area.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding returns.</strong> Every GBP photo, blog image, and location page image adds a small entity signal that compounds over months.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to geotag an image</h2>
        <p>Three ways depending on where the photo comes from.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># 1. Automatic on mobile</span><br>
          Camera app → Location Services <span class="uf-status">ON</span><br>
          EXIF fields written: <span class="uf-new">GPSLatitude, GPSLongitude, GPSAltitude</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 2. Desktop upload (ExifTool)</span><br>
          exiftool -GPSLatitude=<span class="uf-new">"39.7392"</span> \<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-GPSLongitude=<span class="uf-new">"-104.9903"</span> \<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-GPSLatitudeRef=N -GPSLongitudeRef=W \<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;storefront-denver.jpg<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 3. Web tool: GeoImgr, GeoSetter, Adobe Lightroom</span><br>
          Upload → drop pin on map → download tagged file
        </div>

        <h3>Filename + alt text still matter more</h3>
        <p>Descriptive filenames (<code>storefront-denver-co.jpg</code>) and alt text describing the location outrank EXIF coordinates as ranking signals. Do both.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Where geotagged images live</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
