        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real geotagging examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Denver plumber — GBP photo optimisation</h3>
        <p>Uploaded 30 geotagged storefront and job-site photos to Google Business Profile with matching filenames like <code>emergency-plumber-denver-co.jpg</code>. Within eight weeks, direction requests rose 40% and calls from Google grew by 3-5 per week.</p>

        <h3>2. Multi-location restaurant chain</h3>
        <p>A 12-location restaurant standardised its GBP photo pipeline: every location's photos are geotagged with its address, renamed with the city and neighbourhood, and uploaded weekly. GBP impressions rose 60% over six months across the portfolio.</p>

        <h3>3. Hair salon — the counter-example</h3>
        <p>A salon that skipped geotagging while competitors implemented it saw a slow decline in the local pack for its neighbourhood term. After six months of catching up (geotagging + review response + weekly posts), it recovered.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Image geotagging vs geotag (social)</h2>
        <p>Same word, different mechanism. One is metadata inside the file. The other is a platform label on the post.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Image geotagging works for</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Google Business Profile photos</li>
              <li>Local landing page images</li>
              <li>Google Maps place page contributions</li>
              <li>Local SEO entity reinforcement</li>
              <li>Long-term ranking signal decay resistance</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Social geotag (label) works for</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Instagram, TikTok, Facebook posts</li>
              <li>Discovery via location feeds</li>
              <li>Event and venue reach</li>
              <li>Real-time social engagement lift</li>
              <li>UGC aggregation at business locations</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for geotagging images</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Match coordinates to your GBP pin exactly.</strong> Grab the lat/lng from Google Maps and use the same values across all business photos.</li>
          <li><strong>Rename files descriptively.</strong> <code>storefront-denver-co.jpg</code> beats <code>IMG_1042.jpg</code>. This matters more than EXIF for organic ranking.</li>
          <li><strong>Add descriptive alt text.</strong> "Storefront exterior at 500 Main St, Denver, CO" — location context in visible alt text does more than metadata.</li>
          <li><strong>Batch-process before upload.</strong> Use ExifTool or Lightroom to tag folders at once — never rely on manual per-file editing.</li>
          <li><strong>Upload weekly, not once.</strong> GBP rewards fresh photos. A drip beats a dump.</li>
          <li><strong>Strip EXIF from customer-facing brand images that go to social.</strong> Social platforms strip it anyway, and it's a security best practice on public assets.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — geotagging every photo to the head office</div>
          <p>Chains that geotag all photos to headquarters instead of the specific outlet address confuse Google's local entity resolution. Each location's photos should have that location's coordinates, not the corporate pin.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common image geotagging mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Geotagging once and stopping</strong> — GBP rewards a photo cadence, not a bulk upload event.</li>
          <li><strong>Coordinates don't match the GBP address</strong> — creates conflicting entity signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping filename and alt text</strong> — EXIF alone isn't enough; visible signals matter more.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-encoding on the server</strong> — some CMSs strip EXIF on upload. Check with an EXIF viewer.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming social platforms preserve it</strong> — Instagram, TikTok, Facebook all strip EXIF. Use the platform's built-in geotag instead.</li>
        </ul>

